[38;5;129m│[0m submitted, it was evaluated as Python code rather than being displayed as    [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m literal text.                                                                [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m                                                                              [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m Key observations:                                                            [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m 1. The server header reveals `Werkzeug/3.1.7 Python/3.10.20` - indicating    [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m Flask/Jinja2 stack                                                           [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m 2. The thank you message directly echoes the user-provided name, confirming  [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m user input is rendered in the template                                       [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m 3. The vulnerability allowed full Python code execution through Jinja2       [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m template syntax                                                              [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m 4. Using Python's MRO (Method Resolution Order) and subclass enumeration, we [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m could access `__builtins__` and execute arbitrary Python code                [38;5;129m│[0m
[38;5;129m│[0m 5. This is a common vulnerability pattern where developers use string        [38;5;129m│[0m
